d to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"Count","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earl","meanings":["North American: from the title originally adopted as a nickname parallel to   Duke  ,   King  , etc. The title was used in England in Norman times as an equivalent of the French <i>comte</i> ‘count’ it is from Old English <i>eorl</i> ‘warrior, nobleman, prince’. In some cases the given name may have been taken from the surname <i>Earl</i>, which was originally either a nickname or a term denoting someone who worked in the household of an earl."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Guillaume I Count de Sancerre was born about 1170. He had at least 1 daughter with Marie de Charenton. He died in 1217, at the age of 48."},"et":{"Abt 1170–1217":"umbes 1170–1217","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1192–1247":"1192–1247","1170–1217":"1170–1217","1217":"1217","1247":"1247","Abt 1170":"umbes 1170","1192":"1192","1170":"1170","Sancerre, Cher, Centre-Val de Loire, France":"Sancerre, Cher, Centre, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1170–1217":"noin 1170–1217","